          <div class="profile-section mb-6">
            <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Relationship vs. Task Orientation</h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300"><strong>Primarily task-oriented</strong> with a "business first, relationship second" approach. Americans typically move quickly to substantive issues with limited small talk before negotiations.</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="profile-section mb-6">
            <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Decision-Making</h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300"><strong>Relatively fast-paced</strong> with emphasis on efficiency and "time is money." Decision-makers often have significant autonomy, and legal contracts are binding and detailed.</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="profile-section mb-6">
            <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Negotiation Approach</h4>
            <p class="text-gray-300">Competitive but problem-solving oriented with focus on facts, data, and logical arguments. ROI and bottom-line impact are persuasive, and Americans are comfortable with "win-win" framing.</p>
          </div>
          
          <div class="profile-section mb-6">
            <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Persuasion Techniques</h4>
            <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-gray-300">
              <li>Use hard data, ROI metrics, and clear comparisons</li>
              <li>Appeal to efficiency and innovation</li>
              <li>Emphasize short-term gains and competitive advantage</li>
              <li>Present multiple options and alternatives</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          
          <div class="profile-section"> {/* No mb-6 on last item in card */}
            <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Key Considerations</h4>
            <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-gray-300">
              <li>Americans may seem impatient or overly direct to negotiators from relationship-focused cultures</li>
              <li>Legal aspects of agreements are taken very seriously</li>
              <li>Expect preparation and homework on the business case</li>
              <li>Individual achievement and initiative are highly valued</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    
    {/* Germany */}
    <div class="bg-card rounded-xl p-8">
      <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-6 text-violet-200">Germany</h3>
      <div class="culture-profile">
        <div class="profile-section mb-6">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Communication Style</h4>
          <p class="mb-3 text-gray-300"><strong>Very direct and explicit</strong> communication with detailed, precise language and little ambiguity. Germans take a factual, analytical approach and provide thorough written documentation.</p>
          <div class="bg-dark p-3 rounded border border-gray-700 italic text-gray-400 text-sm">
            <p>"Your proposal does not meet our quality standards. We require ISO 9001 certification."</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="profile-section mb-6">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Relationship vs. Task Orientation</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300"><strong>Strongly task-oriented</strong> with formal business relationships. Germans typically maintain limited personal disclosure in business settings and clear separation between business and personal life.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="profile-section mb-6">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Decision-Making</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300"><strong>Methodical and thorough</strong> with decisions based on analysis and expertise. There is respect for hierarchy but with input from experts, and careful planning before commitment.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="profile-section mb-6">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Negotiation Approach</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300">Structured and systematic with strong emphasis on rules, procedures, and standards. Detailed preparation is expected, and Germans typically take a risk-averse approach to new proposals.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="profile-section mb-6">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Persuasion Techniques</h4>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-gray-300">
            <li>Present logical, well-structured arguments</li>
            <li>Provide comprehensive technical specifications</li>
            <li>Demonstrate adherence to quality standards and certifications</li>
            <li>Show long-term reliability and stability</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="profile-section">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Key Considerations</h4>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-gray-300">
            <li>Germans value punctuality and precise scheduling</li>
            <li>Titles and formal address are important</li>
            <li>Humor is generally kept separate from business discussions</li>
            <li>Thoroughness is valued over speed</li>
            <li>Contracts are detailed and followed strictly</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    {/* China */}
    <div class="bg-card rounded-xl p-8">
      <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-6 text-violet-200">China</h3>
      <div class="culture-profile">
        <div class="profile-section mb-6">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Communication Style</h4>
          <p class="mb-3 text-gray-300"><strong>Indirect and contextual</strong> communication where reading between the lines is essential. Face-saving is critical (avoid causing embarrassment), and non-verbal cues carry significant meaning.</p>
          <div class="bg-dark p-3 rounded border border-gray-700 italic text-gray-400 text-sm space-y-1">
            <p>"That might be difficult" (meaning "no")</p>
            <p>"We will consider it" (often means "we disagree but don't want to say so directly")</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="profile-section mb-6">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Relationship vs. Task Orientation</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300"><strong>Strongly relationship-oriented</strong> (guanxi) with substantial time invested in relationship building. Trust development precedes substantive negotiations, and business and personal relationships often blend.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="profile-section mb-6">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Decision-Making</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300"><strong>Hierarchical</strong> but with consultation. Senior leaders make final decisions, consensus building occurs within the hierarchy, and patience is required as decisions move up the chain.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="profile-section mb-6">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Negotiation Approach</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300">Strategic and long-term oriented, potentially using delays and ambiguity as tactics. Multiple negotiators with specialized roles may be present, and Chinese negotiators are comfortable with silence and indirect refusals.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="profile-section mb-6">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Persuasion Techniques</h4>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-gray-300">
            <li>Emphasize long-term partnership potential</li>
            <li>Highlight stability and security aspects</li>
            <li>Reference successful relationships with similar organizations</li>
            <li>Show respect for Chinese culture and achievements</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="profile-section">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Key Considerations</h4>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-gray-300">
            <li>Saving face is crucial—never cause public embarrassment</li>
            <li>Intermediaries can help build trust and relationships</li>
            <li>Contracts may be viewed as starting points rather than final agreements</li>
            <li>Patience and relationship investment yield long-term rewards</li>
            <li>Group harmony and collective interests are prioritized</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    {/* Japan */}
    <div class="bg-card rounded-xl p-8">
      <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-6 text-violet-200">Japan</h3>
      <div class="culture-profile">
        <div class="profile-section mb-6">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Communication Style</h4>
          <p class="mb-3 text-gray-300"><strong>Highly indirect and contextual</strong> with emphasis on harmony (wa) and avoiding conflict. Non-verbal communication is crucial, and what is not said may be more important than what is said.</p>
          <div class="bg-dark p-3 rounded border border-gray-700 italic text-gray-400 text-sm space-y-1">
            <p>Silence, hesitation, or changing the subject often indicates disagreement</p>
            <p>"We will need to examine this further" (likely means "no")</p>
          </div>
        </div>
         <div class="profile-section mb-6">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Relationship vs. Task Orientation</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300"><strong>Strongly relationship-oriented</strong> with extensive time devoted to relationship building. Group consensus is valued over individual positions, and formal business etiquette is essential.</p>
        </div>
         <div class="profile-section mb-6">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Decision-Making</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300"><strong>Consensus-based</strong> (ringi system) with decisions requiring consultation at multiple levels. There is emphasis on group harmony, and the process can be time-consuming.</p>
        </div>
         <div class="profile-section mb-6">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Negotiation Approach</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300">Patient and methodical with discomfort around confrontation or direct disagreement. Silence is used strategically, and detailed preparation and information gathering are expected.</p>
        </div>
         <div class="profile-section mb-6">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Persuasion Techniques</h4>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-gray-300">
            <li>Emphasize long-term stability and reliability</li>
            <li>Show respect for tradition and hierarchy</li>
            <li>Demonstrate commitment to quality and continuous improvement</li>
            <li>Present information in detailed written form</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
         <div class="profile-section">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Key Considerations</h4>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-gray-300">
            <li>Business cards (meishi) exchanged with great ceremony</li>
            <li>Hierarchy and seniority are respected</li>
            <li>Patience is essential—rushing decisions is counterproductive</li>
            <li>"No" is rarely stated directly; listen for hesitation</li>
            <li>Group decision-making takes precedence over individual authority</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    {/* Southeast Asia */}
    <div class="bg-card rounded-xl p-8">
      <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-6 text-violet-200">Southeast Asia</h3>
      <p class="mb-6 text-gray-300">While Southeast Asian countries have distinct cultures, some common patterns exist across Thailand, Vietnam, Indonesia, and Malaysia:</p>
      
      <div class="culture-profile">
        <div class="profile-section mb-6">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Communication Style</h4>
          <p class="mb-3 text-gray-300"><strong>Generally indirect and contextual</strong> with high-context communication requiring interpretation. Politeness and face-saving are important, and relationship-building communication often precedes business talk.</p>
          <div class="bg-dark p-3 rounded border border-gray-700 italic text-gray-400 text-sm space-y-1">
            <p>"Maybe we can discuss this later" (may indicate disagreement)</p>
            <p>Avoiding direct eye contact can signal respect or disagreement depending on context.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="profile-section mb-6">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Relationship vs. Task Orientation</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300"><strong>Predominantly relationship-oriented</strong> where personal connections and trust are fundamental. Hospitality and social activities are often integral to business, and family/community connections matter.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="profile-section mb-6">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Decision-Making</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300">Often <strong>hierarchical</strong> with respect for authority, but varies. It can range from centralized (e.g., Vietnam) to more consultative (e.g., Indonesia). Family structures influence decisions in family businesses, and cultural/religious values play a role.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="profile-section mb-6">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Negotiation Approach</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300">Preference for harmony and compromise, with discomfort around direct confrontation. Patience and relationship-building are rewarded, often leading to more flexibility on terms and implementation later.</p>
        </div>
         <div class="profile-section mb-6">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Persuasion Techniques</h4>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-gray-300">
            <li>Show respect for local customs, hierarchy, and elders</li>
            <li>Emphasize mutual benefits, harmony, and community impact</li>
            <li>Demonstrate long-term commitment to the relationship and region</li>
            <li>Build rapport through social interaction</li>
            <li>Adapt to local business practices and expectations</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
         <div class="profile-section">
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2 text-accent">Key Regional Variations & Considerations</h4>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 text-gray-300">
            <li><strong>Thailand:</strong> Strong respect for hierarchy, conflict avoidance ("kreng jai"), Buddhist influences.</li>
            <li><strong>Vietnam:</strong> Can be more direct than others in the region, hierarchical, importance of relationship-building through shared meals.</li>
            <li><strong>Indonesia:</strong> Value placed on consensus ("musyawarah"), religious considerations (Islam), indirect communication for harmony.</li>
            <li><strong>Malaysia:</strong> Multicultural influences (Malay, Chinese, Indian), relationship-oriented but adapting Western practices, religious considerations (Islam), respect for age/position.</li>
            <li>Across the region, face-saving is important; avoid causing embarrassment.</li>
            <li>Building personal trust is key before diving deep into business specifics.</li>
          </ul>
